This may not be any help, but:
In my children's experience drawing and writing have been very different.
dd#1 (age 6) didn't really draw and, as you've commented on your ds,
generally when she did they weren't as good as others. She didn't start
trying to draw something until she was relatively old to her peers (she was
over 4yo), before she would just do patterns on the paper, certainly for
well after she was writing fluently. But I noticed once she was trying to
draw, say people, she would carefully put in every detail, like pupils in
the eyes, and a tummy button (even when dressed). But her writing is
beautiful, and she loves doing it (particularly on her terms like story
writing at home). She's not that keen on drawing and (particularly for a
girl!!) not that keen on colouring although she puts up with a bit. She had
to be taught how to hold the pencil correctly and even now occasionally
needs some reminding.
dd#2 (age 3) loves drawing and painting and was trying to draw particular
things by 2yo. Her drawings aren't brilliant, but she usually makes an
effort to make it "something", with some resemblance. But she doesn't like
writing for long. She'll do a few letters, like her name, but, although
she's capable of doing most of her letters she doesn't choose to most of the
time. If she's doing writing you're quite likely to find her doing some of
it with her mouth or feet as well as the hand although she naturally holds
the pencil correctly with her hand. She doesn't seem to enjoy writing in the
way #1 did.

