From #1s experience I'd avoid anything like handwriting practice. In her
year they're now doing joined up writing. She loves writing when it's saying
something, but hates the practice handwriting she has to do. I've agreed
with the teacher that she doesn't need to do the repeating a single set of
letters over and over again, but instead can make up her own sentences with
the letters she's learning how to join up. That seems to be much better for
her.
What really got her writing going was writing postal letters.The year she
learnt to write she used to write letters to Granny and friends a lot. Maybe
if you could find someone who would write back for your ds it would be an
incentive. Or could you find some free stuff he would have to write off for?
Maybe if you printed a letter off at first and he has to fill in missing
words might be less daunting at first.

I waswondering how his fine motor control is too? It may be no problem, but
it might be something he doesn't do so much of, so working on that might
help a bit with pencil control.
I think you've said before he's quiet into experiment/science? He might like
some of those little electric (battery powered) games where you have to move
a ring round a piece of curly wire without touching it or it makes a buzzing
noise (I hope you know what I mean because I don't know what they're called)

