Stephanie,

I don't see Jeff's suggestions as at all derogatory.  Given the school
setting your child is in, my own suggestion would be special ed,
tutoring (in-school peers, adult private tutor), or homeschooling (in
addition to the regular school) to teach handwriting.  All of these
choices applying only if you think your child is ready to learn
handwriting.

My 2yo knows all his letters and numbers, and can read and spell a few
words.  He knows where all the letters and numbers are on a qwerty
keyboard, and he can type his own userid and password, launch his
browser and navigate his favorite online children's games.  And he has
mastered all mouse functions except cut&amp;paste (he can cut, but does
not see any point to paste).  He loves to drag things into the trash,
and use scrollbars.  He has typed letters on the computer since he was
5 months old and has chosen the letters to type by name for over a
year now.  He can count to 10 and has begun simple addition and can
tell time.  Yet he has barely begun to write by hand.  One day I found
him tracing letters printed large size on a piece of paper.  He is
learning the alphabet song.

School isn't so much about learning in lockstep with other children as
about learning foundation skills before being presented with skills
that build on those foundations.  You may reject lockstep schooling,
but take care that you do not let your child skip learning necessary
foundations!

To decide if you want to homeschool, try starting now at shadowing his
teachers' work with him.  Ie, know what he is learning now, how well
it is going, and think ahead.  What should your child be learning a
few weeks from now, a few months from now?  What techniques and
materials would you use to teach him?  Are there any holes in his
education now?  It is work!  Have a work plan.
</POST>
