It sounds like you already talked to the school about it, but if you
haven't formally requested testing it might be useful.  Particularly
if his skills in one area are dramatically out of step with his skills
in other areas it's worth seeing if there's any neuropsych (ie, brain-
wiring) reason for it.  I'm not sure how much of my knowledge is state-
specific, but at least in California the school district is
responsible for doing such testing on anyone above age three whether
or not they're enrolled in public school, though I suspect
logistically it would probably be easier to do it while he's still in
public school.  If you send a written request for evaluation they're
obligated to do it within a certain time frame regardless of his
overall academic performance.  You could just wait and see or try
another curriculum first but I'm not sure I see the downside of a free
evaluation that carries no obligation to do anything in particular.

