One of my kids' teachers (can't remember which one) had him use those rubber
grip things on the pencil to help him hold it in the proper place, and to
prevent him from having the "death grip" on the pencil. Kids that can't
write well often experience real pain in their hands from gripping the
pencil. She also let him use a pen, the ink gliding over the paper makes
writing easier than using a graphite pencil.

My three boys ( 17, 13, 9) all have *awful* handwriting, always did, always
will I suppose, like my husband does.  The youngest has the best, but he's a
lefty, which has it's own problems.
I think this is a skill that comes much later to boys, and they don't seem
to care about it as much as girls do - I'm 42 and I still take care to have
nice handwriting!
As my boys progressed through the grades in school it became much less
important - their handwriting hasn't gotten appreciably better , but they
are no longer graded on it. It's just something they have to suffer through,
I guess, until they are able to use computers to write all their
assignments.

Interestingly, the only men I know personally that have lovely handwriting
are my dad (also a lefty) and my boss, and they both have engineering
degrees.
